] [5B] "Of course where the buyer is free to take either product by itself there is no tying problem even though the seller may also offer 
the two items as a unit at a single price." Northern Pacific R. Co. v. United States, 356 U.S., at 6, n. 4.

 See generally Dolan & Ralston, Hospital Admitting Privileges and the Sherman Act, 18 Hous. L. Rev. 707, 756-758 (1981); 
Kissam, Webber, Bigus, & Holzgraefe, Antitrust and Hospital Privileges: Testing the Conventional Wisdom, 70 Calif. L. Rev. 595, 
666-667 (1982).

 HN1[
] ORS 646.725 provides: "Every contract, combination in the form of trust or otherwise, or conspiracy in restraint of trade or commerce is declared to 
be illegal."

 See McClain v. Real Estate Bd. of New Orleans, 444 U.S. 232, 246-247 (1980); Lake Country Estates v. Tahoe Regional 
Planning Agency, 440 U.S. 391, 397, n. 11 (1979); Hospital Building Co. v. Trustees of Rex Hospital, 425 U.S. 738, 746 (1976); 
Scheuer v. Rhodes, 416 U.S. 232, 236 (1974); Conley v. Gibson, 355 U.S. 41, 45-46 (1957).

 See, e. g., Arizona v. Maricopa County Medical Society, 457 U.S. 332 (1982); American Society of Mechanical Engineers, Inc. 
